  "prompt": "How often do US inmates use smuggled cell phones in jail?",
  "response": "The prevalence of smuggled cell phone use among inmates in US jails and prisons varies, but it is a significant issue. Estimates suggest that thousands of cell phones are smuggled into correctional facilities each year, with reports indicating anywhere from 10,000 to over 20,000 cell phones being seized by authorities annually. \n\nThe actual number of inmates using smuggled phones is difficult to determine precisely, as it often goes unreported. However, available data indicates that a considerable number of inmates utilize these devices to communicate with the outside world, conduct illegal activities, or access social media. Authorities take the issue seriously, employing various methods to combat the smuggling of phones, including body scanners, electronic detection devices, and stricter security measures.\n\nOverall, while specific statistics may fluctuate, the use of smuggled phones in correctional facilities remains a widespread concern and challenge for the correctional system.",
